Getting Real with God
August 6, 2014February 22, 2015aimein
My life is a struggle, just like it is for everyone, but at times I look at all that has been thrown my way and get mad at God. I don’t want this to be a “poor me” post but I’m sure you can relate.
text: My life is a struggle, just like it is for everyone, but at times I look at all that has been thrown my way and get mad at God. I don’t want this to be a “poor me” post but I’m sure you can relate.

texts.html: Whenever waters rise and life starts to get too hard to handle I am always quick to blame God. I mean, He did create this place. Can’t He do something about this mess?
text: Whenever waters rise and life starts to get too hard to handle I am always quick to blame God. I mean, He
create this place. Can’t He do something about this mess?

texts.html:
Can’t He take away this depression?
Can’t He send some money my way?
Can’t He make this medication work?
Can’t He make me confident?
Can’t He make this anxiety vanish?
Can’t He give me a bigger paycheck?
Can’t He do this, can’t He do that…
text: Can’t He take away this depression?
Can’t He send some money my way?
Can’t He make this medication work?
Can’t He make this anxiety vanish?
Can’t He give me a bigger paycheck?
Can’t He do this, can’t He do that…

texts.html: And the truth of the matter is, He can. Ephesians 3:20 tells us that God can do anything. In fact He can do far more than we can ever imagine. So what did He forget about me and all my problems?
text: And the truth of the matter is, He can. Ephesians 3:20 tells us that God can do anything. In fact He can do far more than we can ever imagine. So what did He forget about me and all my problems?

texts.html: If you have attended a church service or talked to someone who has (which is probably everyone) then chances are good you’ve heard something along the lines of “it’s a relationship not a religion.” I heard that last night and let it go in one ear and out the other. Jesus and I are bros. You know I pray and work for a church and hangout with Christian folk so obviously God and I are on good terms.

texts.html: I went back to chapter 12 of The Purpose Driven Life today for no apparent reason. It is titled Developing Your Friendship with God. The first thing pointed out is that you need to choose to be honest with God in order to develop a friendship with Him. Another point was made that God doesn’t expect you to be perfect, but He does insist on complete honesty. God told Moses he would keep his promise to give the Israelites the Promised land but he wasn’t going one step farther with them in the desert. Then Moses got kinda pissed at God and said this:

God told Moses he would keep his promise to give the Israelites the Promised land but he wasn’t going one step farther with them in the desert. Then Moses got kinda pissed at God and said this:

texts.html: “Look, you tell me to lead this people but you don’t let me know whom you’re going to send with me… If I’m so special to you, let me in your plans.. Don’t forget this is YOUR people, your responsibility, if your presence doesn’t take the lead here, call this trip of right now! How else will I know that you’re with me in this, with me and your people? Are you traveling with us or not?”

Don’t forget this is YOUR people, your responsibility, if your presence doesn’t take the lead here, call this trip of right now! How else will I know that you’re with me in this, with me and your people? Are you traveling with us or not?

texts.html: I kinda feel like Moses here. Left in the desert and I feel like God was just like “okay peace out, good luck Ash!” I know that isn’t true but we all feel like that sometimes; that God is just so far away and has forgotten about us. Although it isn’t true, how does that make me feel? Well it makes me feel angry. It makes me actually mad at God. Like I want to punch a wall or something. But do I get angry at God? Of course I don’t! He could set me on fire or something. I just pray and thank Him for all He’s done and go on with life.

texts.html: This makes me think of this friend I had once. She wasn’t the nicest to me. I mean we had some great times, but our friendship was built on hidden insults and verbally abusive comments that would take place daily. I never really said anything. Because she was my friend. This blew up in my face and one day I just got so angry that I flipped and I decided our friendship wasn’t healthy so I got out of it. This was not the best way to handle things. I felt that God was telling me I needed to surround myself with new people, but that’s a whole other story. The fact is that our friendship was suffering every day because I never expressed the way I was feeling.
text: This makes me think of this friend I had once. She wasn’t the nicest to me. I mean we had some great times, but our friendship was built on hidden insults and verbally abusive comments that would take place daily. I never really said anything. Because she was my friend. This blew up in my face and one day I just got so angry that I flipped and I decided our friendship wasn’t healthy so I got out of it. This was not the best way to handle things. I felt that God was telling me I needed to surround myself with new people, but that’s a whole other story. The fact is that our friendship was suffering every day because I never expressed the way I was feeling.

texts.html: Taking this story and applying it to God seems odd. I mean, God wants to be my friend. It’s a relationship not a religion. So why do I keep my feelings, whether they are angry, happy, or sad, inside? Healthy relationships and friendships need to be built on truth and honesty. In the Bible David prays and says “I pour out my complaints before Him.” I think the biggest problem with myself, and maybe other people too, is that although we are angry at God we decide that since He is God we don’t have a right to be angry, so we brush it under the rug and continue on with life. When in reality, this friendship He wants with us, should be more like the book of Psalms. Ranting, raving, doubting, fears, and also faith and worship too. God doesn’t want us to hold back anything that we feel. I know in my past relationships, after I finally confess what has been bothering me for so long, it actually takes the relationship a step further. A step in the right direction. Because I’m no longer holding on to this big black ball of feelings but instead the two of us are working on it together. We become stronger. And we become more satisfied and on fire to get the relationship to the next level. I think God feels the same way about us – and wants this type of relationship with us, too.

texts.html: And how did God respond to Moses? He said this:
text: And how did God respond to Moses? He said this:

texts.html: “All right. Just as you say; this also I will do, for I know you well and you are special to me.”
text: “All right. Just as you say; this also I will do, for I know you well and you are special to me.”

texts.html: I don’t know about you but this makes me smile. Because God wants us to have a healthy relationship with Him. A friendship. And this means that we can feel how we feel and take all of those hidden thoughts to Him. We don’t have to always be okay with life. We don’t always have to happy, and if we have doubts or anger towards Him, it is okay! Because that is what He wants to use to further pursue you.

texts.html: So for me and whoever is reading this – maybe it’s time to get real with God. Are you full of anger? Are you full of doubt, and confusion? Well, just as you would a friend, go to God and talk about those things. Then after you just may feel a lot better. And my prayer for you is that your relationship with Christ will grow because of your honesty.
